        <para>A monograph does not <em>have</em> to occur inside something else, but it can, since it can be part of a series. 
            If we want to register that a monograph belongs to a series, we usually need only note the series title and the location of the monograph inside the series, i.e. its volume number (if it is numbered). </para>
        <ul>
            <li>
                <span class="publication">Markman, Charles W. Chicago before History: The Prehistoric Archaeology of a Modern Metropolitan Area</span>. <span class="container">Studies in Illinois Archaeology</span>
                <span class="location">7</span>.
                <span class="publication">Springfield: Illinois Historic Preservation Agency, 1991</span>. </li>
            <li>
                <span class="publication">Isenberg, Nancy. Sex and Citizenship in Antebellum America.</span>
                <span class="container">Gender and American Culture</span>. <span class="publication">Chapel Hill: University of North Carolina Press,
                1998</span>.</li>
        </ul>
        <para>The different parts are differently coloured: <span class="publication">publication</span>, <span class="container">container</span> and <span class="location">location</span> of publication inside container. </para>
        <para>Note that the last monograph has no location in the monograph series it occurs in - the series may be unnumbered. Note also that the information regarding container and location inside container splits the information regarding the publication in two.</para>
        <para>It is not very often that one wishes to catalogue a series on its own, but for reasons of parallelism it is included in the Basic Input Forms.
            A series has a title, one or more editors, and the series as a whole has a place and time of publication, as well as an extent: 
            the number of volumes published hitherto. We see that one would normally note more pieces information than when cataloguing a monograph as part of a series. 
            The same holds for periodicals, as we shall see.</para>
